The chemical structure of AFB1 was similar to that of DMC (Fig. 2
                        ). Particularly, AFB1 and DMC bound MAA similarly [13]. Additionally, DMC was cheaper than AFB1 and non-toxic. Therefore, DMC was used as an alternative template, and MAA was used as functional monomer. The obtained CDs-DMIP column exhibited a uniform, plump structure (Fig. 3
                        a), and the polymers showed regular pores (Fig. 3d and e). AM was also tested as the functional monomer, but the synthesized capillary column (Fig. 3b) was less full than that using MAA, and the polymers were washed out at a low pressure. Thus, MAA was selected as the functional monomer. The performance of CDs-DMIP column was also boosted by studying its polymerization. The photopolymerization of CDs-DMIP column was incomplete (Fig. 3c), but the column synthesized by in-situ polymerization had uniform, full features. Furthermore, CDs-DMIP monolithic column had been successfully synthesized with MAA by in-situ polymerization (Fig. 1c), as evidenced by the well-defined characteristic peaks at 1730cm−1(CO), 1615cm−1(CC), 1263cm−1(CO) and 1150cm−1(CO).The peak intensity of CO stretching vibration (1730cm−1) originated from MAA and EDMA, and the symmetry vibration of CO at 1150cm−1 was from EDMA. The asymmetric stretching vibration peak of SiOSi was located at 1060cm−1, and the peaks at 806cm−1 and 473cm−1 could be assigned to SiO vibrations. Collectively, CDs-DMIP column had been successfully synthesized, emitting blue FL for a long time under UV lamp at 365nm (Fig. S4).
